ed States are going to happen whether U.S. troops stay or go. The more widely predicted negative consequences of leaving are a full-blown Iraqi civil war and al Qaeda using Iraq as a base of operations."/><meta property="fb:admins" content="91480005965"/><meta itemprop="name" content="Americans Favor Iraq Timetable, Don't Foresee Increased Terrorism"/><meta itemprop="description" content="About 6 in 10 Americans favor setting a firm timetable for withdrawing U.S. troops from Iraq, while 36% would rather keep troops in Iraq until the situation there improves. A majority of Americans say terrorist attacks against the United States are going to happen whether U.S. troops stay or go. The more widely predicted negative consequences of leaving are a full-blown Iraqi civil war and al Qaeda using Iraq as a base of operations."/></head>

